…then you will, and it’s awful. This passes. 

Laugh. Hold the ones you love & laugh at stupid things & wonderful memories. 

The first day you wake up & feel ‘normal’ is weird as fuck & makes you feel like an awful human. 

Assume you won’t feel normal tomorrow.

…do things like book the restaurant, bring food, cook food etc. Most people won’t want to intrude - I would have been the same - but we need you as we can’t really think straight right now. 

You will wake up the morning after & for a second you won’t remember & it’s lovely…

Shock is not permanent, but it’s weird when it lasts days not hours. Turns out paper bags in the kitchen come in useful when you hyperventilate & sugar in tea is a winner. Even if you normally hate sugar in tea. 

You don’t know what you want, so better for friends to just…

…& teasing your stomach with small dishes regularly, works. Also pudding for dinner is allowed. 

Animals just know. They won’t leave your side. 

Exhaustion will be off the charts. Currently doing one day ‘on’, one day in bed. 

It will be too easy to drink too much.

Things I’ve learnt about grief in a week: 

🧵👇
Texts from friends starting ‘you don’t have to reply, just wanted you to know…’ - I’ve not had the ability to text more than a 💜 at times, so not feeling pressured to do more is very helpful. 

Your appetite will come back…

I would like to go back to that 16 year old & teach her what I know now. But I can't. So I hope this thread helps someone out there thinking they are a 'fake' bisexual or who is also grieving for what they didn't get to experience. You're awesome. I'm awesome. We're awesome 🏳️‍🌈👩‍❤️‍👩

A while back I met a woman who made me tingle in my toes when we spoke. As I said, I'm in a committed relationship so nothing ever happened, but when I tingled I was instantly 16 again, wanting to kiss a girl & feeling unable & unworthy. It sucked.

I lost a chance to explore who I am, and instead hid and was ashamed of that part of myself for decades. And to know that I am still not 'Bi enough' for quite a lot of people is yet again saying 'fake bisexual over there!'

...and accused of either being a lesbian (bad) or a fake one (worse?). 

To this day I have absolutely no idea how to chat up women. So I don't. I like men, I love my boyfriend, I don't need to date anymore (hopefully!) so does it matter? 

To me, yes it does.

...attract men. That I was doing it for attention. And that as I hadn't dated a woman, I was obviously not a lesbian (which I never claimed to be!). It became impossible to actually connect with a girl & flirt/see if she was into me without acute anxiety that I would be misread

As I got older & started going out to clubs I met women I fancied, but to even look at another woman was to be 100% the focus of the male gaze. Everything you did was for them - according to both them and those watching the men watch us. I was accused of kissing girls to....

I fell in love a hundred times with characters - mostly the men, but the women popped up at times too. As I got older I realised that sometimes, I was attracted to women too. But I wasn't going to make the same mistake as I did in year 8. I kept my mouth shut.

That was it. 2 years of no friends and hiding in the library reading books. This was how I survived. Losing myself in Anne Rice fantasy & John Grisham thrillers. And I got the message: Gay = bad. There was no online community back then so it was just me and the library.

...gay people (It was mostly gay men - I don't remember meeting any lesbians at the time. Probably says a lot about the culture/sexism/lesbophobia at the time). When someone said something homophobic in school I didn't even realise homophobia was a thing and defended my friends.

I grew up under section 28 & for 2 years at school no-one spoke to me as I was the school 'dyke'. This had nothing to do with my own sexuality - I was part of the theatre outside of school & had gay friends, & my dad worked in TV so I grew up in green rooms surrounded by...
